content:
Java ignores all whitespace in front of a statement. As this, these two code snippets are identical for the compiler:Code section 2.15: Indented code


 1 public static void main(String[] args) {
 2   Distance dist = new Distance(
 3            intValue(args[0]), intValue(args[1]),
 4            intValue(args[2]), intValue(args[3]));
 5   dist.printDistance();
 6 }
 7 
 8 private static int intValue(String data) {
 9   return Integer.parseInt(data);
10 }Code section 2.16: Not indented code


 1 public static void main(String[] args) {
 2 Distance dist = new Distance(
 3 intValue(args[0]), intValue(args[1]),
 4 intValue(args[2]), intValue(args[3]));
 5 dist.printDistance();
 6 }
 7 
 8 private static int intValue(String data) {
 9 return Integer.parseInt(data);
10 }However, the first one's style (with whitespace) is preferred, as the readability is higher. The method body is easier to distinguish from the head, even at a higher reading speed.
